I think it was a little delayed here,

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:07.400
so let me start over again.

00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:10.520
Hi friends, thank you so much for joining us today.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:14.060
Welcome to the RStudio Enterprise Community Meetup.

00:00:14.060 --> 00:00:18.240
I'm Rachel calling in from a rainy Boston today.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:19.600
If you've just joined now,

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:21.780
feel free to say hi through the chat window

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:24.559
and maybe where you're calling in from.

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:27.680
If this is your first time joining one of these sessions,

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:32.200
we do have them every Tuesday at noon Eastern time.

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:35.560
And so I'll share a calendar of all the upcoming events

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:37.520
in the chat in just a second here,

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:40.779
where you can add whole calendar or individual events

00:00:40.779 --> 00:00:42.959
to your own calendar too.

00:00:42.959 --> 00:00:45.799
This is a friendly and open meetup environment

00:00:45.799 --> 00:00:48.540
for teams to share different use cases with each other

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:51.220
and teach lessons learned.

00:00:51.220 --> 00:00:54.599
Together, we're all dedicated to making this an inclusive

00:00:54.599 --> 00:00:57.080
and open environment for everyone,

00:00:57.080 --> 00:01:00.759
no matter your experience, your industry or background.

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:04.320
During the event, you can also ask questions

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:06.620
on the platform that you are watching from.

00:01:07.540 --> 00:01:10.879
You're also able to ask anonymous questions as well

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:15.879
through rstd.io slash meetup questions,

00:01:16.279 --> 00:01:19.379
which I'll put on the screen here in just a second too.

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:23.419
But with all that, welcome.

00:01:23.419 --> 00:01:25.480
Thank you so much for joining us.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:30.199
I would love to pull Ryan up here on stage

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:33.080
and let me handle my little side panel here.

00:01:34.279 --> 00:01:35.120
Hi, Ryan.

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:37.000
Ryan, thanks so much for joining us.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.599
Ryan leads Veterans Affairs quantitative approach

00:01:39.599 --> 00:01:42.080
to improving employee engagement,

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:45.959
primarily through feedback and related outcome data.

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:49.620
Thank you, Ryan, for sharing your experience.

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:50.459
Absolutely.

00:01:50.459 --> 00:01:51.279
Thank you, Rachel.

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:53.360
And thank you all for the time.

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:57.680
So I'll talk about how we use Shiny and rstd.io Connect

00:01:57.680 --> 00:01:59.239
at the Department of Veterans Affairs

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:01.239
for our executive dashboard project.

00:02:02.879 --> 00:02:06.239
So as you probably know,

00:02:06.239 --> 00:02:08.399
VA's mission, which of course I'm here to talk

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:11.839
about our work specifically, not VA more broadly.

00:02:11.839 --> 00:02:16.440
VA's mission is to provide healthcare and benefits

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:19.460
and burial services for U.S. veterans.

00:02:19.460 --> 00:02:22.880
And the mission of my office of NCOD

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:24.880
is to improve employee engagement in VA

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:28.020
so that those services can be provided most effectively.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.240
We do that in the way that's most relevant here

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:35.899
through enterprise survey and data science services.

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:41.220
So some context for that work is that VA is quite large,

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:44.839
as you may know, 400,000 plus employees

00:02:44.839 --> 00:02:48.919
from Manila to San Juan to Maine,

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:51.199
every kind of occupation you can think of,

00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:54.119
hundreds of hospitals and clinics

00:02:54.119 --> 00:02:57.160
and benefits offices and cemeteries.

00:02:58.119 --> 00:03:01.759
So in contrast to that, my office is quite small.

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:03.559
Our headcount is about 50.

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:06.839
So on one hand, that's really exciting

00:03:06.839 --> 00:03:10.119
because we can have a very outsized impact

00:03:10.119 --> 00:03:13.419
and work in a very high leveraged way.

00:03:13.419 --> 00:03:16.600
But it also means we have to punch way above our weight class

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.080
to have the kind of impact that we need to have.

00:03:19.119 --> 00:03:22.720
So some of the tools and processes I can talk about today

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:24.160
are what help us do that.

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:28.399
So just a little bit of info about the data

00:03:28.399 --> 00:03:30.199
that go into the application I'll show you,

00:03:30.199 --> 00:03:32.800
and then we'll, of course, jump into the actual app.

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:38.160
The primary data source from surveys that we use

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:40.660
is something called the All-Employee Survey.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:45.660
And every year, VA administers the AES to every employee,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:47.320
very comprehensive.

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:50.399
It covers everything from engagement to burnout

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:54.119
to psychological safety, patient safety,

00:03:54.119 --> 00:03:56.919
specific modules for specific occupations.

00:03:56.919 --> 00:04:00.279
So there's between 70 and 120 questions

00:04:00.279 --> 00:04:01.880
depending on what you do.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.440
And it's our primary data source for organizational health.

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:09.240
And it's also one of the most important,

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.039
maybe in some ways the most important,

00:04:11.039 --> 00:04:13.440
feedback mechanism that VA has

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.039
for hearing about how we can provide

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:16.559
better services to veterans.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:20.200
It gets a great response rate.

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:23.359
So we have representative high-quality data,

00:04:23.359 --> 00:04:25.480
about 70% response rate this year.

00:04:26.679 --> 00:04:29.760
People feel like they can be honest because it's anonymous.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:33.119
And the data go lots of places

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:35.119
into executives' performance plans

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:38.119
and get reported in important ways.

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:40.000
But from NCOD's perspective,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.880
the most important purpose of the data

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:44.679
is for workgroup-level improvement.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.200
So workgroup is just a group of five or 10 or 15 people

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:51.399
who work together on a day-to-day basis.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:55.679
So for that improvement to happen,

00:04:55.679 --> 00:04:56.600
first of all, of course,

00:04:56.600 --> 00:04:58.040
workgroups need to have their data

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:00.679
and be able to discuss it and see what it's telling them

00:05:00.679 --> 00:05:03.079
and strategize about how to improve

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:04.640
their day-to-day work life.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:09.160
But for purposes today at the executive level,

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:13.200
of course, executives need to know what's going on.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:16.239
Basically, they need to know where there are hotspots,

00:05:16.239 --> 00:05:18.000
things to watch out for,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.040
any trends that may be concerning or noteworthy.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.799
And so the app and the briefing process that we use

00:05:25.799 --> 00:05:29.000
helps get executives that level of data they need

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.720
in a quick way and also in a way that's very durable

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.559
and that they can use as a reference.

00:05:36.279 --> 00:05:39.600
So we brief every executive team in VA,

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:41.440
which is about 300 teams,

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:45.200
2,000, probably closer to 2,500 individuals.

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:48.040
So for example, at a hospital,

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:51.079
the executive team would be the director,

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.160
a few service chiefs,

00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:55.679
and maybe a few other people too.

00:05:55.679 --> 00:05:58.679
So the top four, five, six, seven people at every site.

00:06:00.119 --> 00:06:03.200
And we brief them directly from the dashboard

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:04.559
that I'll show you in just a second.

00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:09.040
So we used to use giant PowerPoints and big Excel files

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:13.239
and those were great as references,

00:06:13.239 --> 00:06:16.079
but as you can imagine, not terribly compelling

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:18.839
when you have the kind of data we have

00:06:18.839 --> 00:06:20.440
at the scale that we have it.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:23.000
So the dashboard's been a huge improvement for us.

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:29.040
Just a few final points about the app itself.

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:32.920
Flat CSV files are our data source,

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:37.040
so no fancy APIs or databases.

00:06:37.239 --> 00:06:40.320
And the displays are also pretty simple as you'll see.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:44.279
We mostly use bar charts, line graphs, and tables.

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:47.559
And I note this here because if you're like me,

00:06:47.559 --> 00:06:50.160
you see some of the really sophisticated and cool apps

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:51.440
that other people make

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:54.040
that do bring in lots of other data sources

00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:56.880
and have lots of cool plugins and so on.

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:58.799
And it's easy, at least for me,

00:06:58.799 --> 00:07:00.720
to think that you have to do that kind of stuff

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:02.359
for it to be useful.

00:07:02.359 --> 00:07:03.760
So for what it's worth,

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:05.119
we've gotten a lot of mileage

00:07:05.119 --> 00:07:09.079
out of pretty simple backends.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:13.839
The other thing you'll see that we put a lot of work into

00:07:13.839 --> 00:07:16.480
is for the interface to look relatively coherent,

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:20.000
hopefully, and for it to be predictable.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Because with the audience we have,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.679
it's just not tenable to expect 2,500 executives

00:07:25.679 --> 00:07:29.040
to learn some idiosyncratic interface

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.239
or deal with fiddly UI issues.

00:07:33.239 --> 00:07:35.559
So it needs to be very predictable,

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:39.079
very polished, and also pretty responsive

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:41.720
because these briefings last for 60 minutes

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:45.959
and that's a lot of time, but also it's not.

00:07:45.959 --> 00:07:49.079
So even if we had a few minutes of cumulative lag

00:07:49.079 --> 00:07:51.679
waiting for things to update or to calculate,

00:07:51.679 --> 00:07:53.799
that's a decent percentage of our total time.

00:07:53.799 --> 00:07:55.880
So those are some considerations

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:59.320
that we've had to deal with while building this application.

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.880
I'll try to pause for questions periodically,

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.440
but feel free to interrupt with any questions

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.359
or points of elaboration you'd like me to make.

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:15.679
So with that, I will change screens, hopefully.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:19.480
I was just gonna say, I'll pop in here

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:21.000
when there are some questions too,

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
but just wanted to remind everyone

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.519
that you can ask either on LinkedIn,

00:08:25.519 --> 00:08:28.959
if you're watching there, or on YouTube Live.

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:32.520
Also, there's the Slido link for anonymous questions too.

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:38.039
And so one of the considerations

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:42.159
that if you do this at scale, you'll run into is bandwidth.

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:46.679
So we have a relatively large backend server,

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:49.119
but when you have hundreds of people

00:08:49.119 --> 00:08:51.119
coming at the same time to it,

00:08:51.119 --> 00:08:52.599
it's gonna sometimes be slow.

00:08:52.599 --> 00:08:57.039
So hopefully we get a pretty good response now

00:08:57.039 --> 00:08:59.239
because actually the briefings are going on right now.

00:08:59.239 --> 00:09:00.880
So I came from one this morning,

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:02.440
I've got one this afternoon.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:05.200
So there's a lot of traffic on this platform right now.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:09.559
So the first thing you see when you go to the link

00:09:09.559 --> 00:09:11.000
that we give to all executives,

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.280
and I'll just make it a full screen,

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:17.840
VA's numbers come up by default.

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:20.960
So one of the good things about doing it in this way

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:23.719
is that it's really easy to be very transparent

00:09:23.719 --> 00:09:26.000
with all the data that we have

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.359
because anybody in VA can pick data for any group in VA.

00:09:31.280 --> 00:09:35.080
So there's no kind of compartmentalizing the information.

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.679
Everything is fully available for anyone to see.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:41.280
The other thing that that makes it very easy to do

00:09:41.280 --> 00:09:45.239
is to go into deep dives on specific groups

00:09:45.239 --> 00:09:48.440
that may be of interest during a particular briefing.

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:52.359
So if we're briefing one of the undersecretaries,

00:09:52.359 --> 00:09:56.039
for example, who are over lots of different facilities

00:09:56.039 --> 00:09:58.440
and they have a question about a specific facility,

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:01.200
we can go right to that facility and this input

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:03.640
and everything else updates with that facility's data.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.840
So it's a great way to be responsive in real time

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:08.960
versus having to take questions

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:11.119
and then come back with additional reports.

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:18.119
So I'll go to our demo page, which has fictitious data.

00:10:19.119 --> 00:10:24.039
So it's representative of what a facility would see,

00:10:24.039 --> 00:10:26.960
but the numbers are not real.

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:32.599
So as I go through this, I'll show you what we have

00:10:32.599 --> 00:10:35.000
and I'll try to focus more on the app itself

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.239
than the data points, which is kind of backwards

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:38.960
from how the briefings would go, of course,

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:41.119
but I'm happy to talk about any of it.

00:10:41.119 --> 00:10:42.799
So feel free to break in with questions

00:10:42.799 --> 00:10:45.400
on the app itself or the data.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:49.080
So the first thing you may notice

00:10:49.080 --> 00:10:51.719
is that it doesn't look like the standard Shiny app

00:10:51.719 --> 00:10:53.440
that you get by default.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:58.559
It's a Bootstrap page running Bootstrap 5

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:01.159
with the bslib package.

00:11:02.359 --> 00:11:04.359
So that gives us a good bit of flexibility

00:11:04.359 --> 00:11:08.320
because then we can use Bootstrap's native row column layout

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:09.840
to get exactly what we want.

00:11:10.440 --> 00:11:13.799
It's also, so you'll notice the picture, for example,

00:11:13.799 --> 00:11:15.359
in the top right.

00:11:15.359 --> 00:11:19.559
So for every facility, we find a story about that facility

00:11:19.559 --> 00:11:24.559
from, that's been published by that facility itself,

00:11:25.559 --> 00:11:27.799
that talks about some service that's been provided

00:11:27.799 --> 00:11:29.919
or some efforts that have been undertaken

00:11:29.919 --> 00:11:33.760
that are what the data we have tried to promote.

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:35.440
So in the case here, this is the picture

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:37.200
from the Chicago VA.

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:40.119
And a lot of VAs do this, and it's really cool.

00:11:40.119 --> 00:11:45.119
They partner with local community service organizations,

00:11:45.119 --> 00:11:47.280
veterans organizations, and so on.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:51.640
And they'll do things like drive-through baby showers.

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.880
So if you're a veteran and your family just had a baby

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.880
and you need some help, you can show up

00:11:56.880 --> 00:11:59.960
and drive through basically a big tunnel

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:02.280
where they load you up with everything

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:03.559
that you need in your car.

00:12:03.679 --> 00:12:06.479
And if you haven't seen the kind of impact

00:12:06.479 --> 00:12:08.719
that that kind of service and work can have,

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:10.400
it's really, really effective.

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:15.840
So we try to tie in what's actually going on

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:18.080
on the ground to the data we have

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:19.440
just to build a connection.

00:12:21.359 --> 00:12:24.000
There's a story that's linked behind the picture

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.119
and I'll not click on it now

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:26.520
just to save the back and forth,

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:29.640
but the actual stories are linked here as well.

00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:32.239
So this is a picture of the Chicago VA

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:33.559
are linked here as well.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:39.320
There's a video that we put behind a,

00:12:39.320 --> 00:12:40.960
it's an embedded YouTube video.

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:43.280
It's in an iframe, and it just sets the tone

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:45.440
for why we do the survey in the first place.

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:48.119
It's not really about tracking a bunch of numbers.

00:12:48.119 --> 00:12:50.599
It's about changing how people experience

00:12:50.599 --> 00:12:52.640
their day-to-day work at VA.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:57.640
And then throughout, you'll also see

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:00.599
a red, yellow, green color heuristic by default

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:05.280
to indicate when a score is good or okay, or not so great.

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:07.000
Of course, some people can't see that,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.400
so it's easy to change to an alternate palette

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:13.159
or to pick a custom palette that anybody can see.

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:17.200
The trick with something like this

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:18.159
that I learned the hard way

00:13:18.159 --> 00:13:20.440
is you wanna bring in the color scheme

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:23.799
as late in the reactive chain as you can

00:13:23.799 --> 00:13:25.799
so that if someone changes the color scheme,

00:13:25.799 --> 00:13:29.479
you're not refiring all the reactives

00:13:29.479 --> 00:13:31.679
that would do data manipulations

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:33.200
that don't need to be redone.

00:13:33.200 --> 00:13:36.400
You wanna just re-skin the graphs, basically.

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:40.520
And it's tedious to do that after you do it the other way,

00:13:40.520 --> 00:13:42.679
so you wanna make sure to do that early on.

00:13:45.719 --> 00:13:47.440
So the first thing we show people

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:49.880
are some key numbers that correspond

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:53.559
to important things that VA leaders care about.

00:13:53.559 --> 00:13:55.280
The response rate, obviously, is important

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:58.799
because you need to know how representative your data are.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.440
Data sharing and data use refer to the extent

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:03.440
that people at that organization say

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:06.039
they've seen their data and that it's been used

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:08.880
to improve their day-to-day work life.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:15.080
So if you do some back-of-the-envelope math,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:17.400
the VA score on this is 42%.

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:21.840
So we're talking about 200,000 people

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:26.280
who say that this specific survey has made improvements

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:29.039
and has led to improvements in how they are able

00:14:29.039 --> 00:14:31.599
to provide their service to veterans.

00:14:31.599 --> 00:14:36.400
Everything from getting pharmacy medications

00:14:36.400 --> 00:14:40.280
turned around quicker from prescription to administration,

00:14:40.280 --> 00:14:43.119
lots of employee wellness activities,

00:14:43.119 --> 00:14:46.559
lots of governance to do with nursing groups.

00:14:46.559 --> 00:14:50.200
So the places that groups go once they start talking

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:51.760
about how they feel about their work

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:53.119
and what can be done better

00:14:54.119 --> 00:14:56.159
are usually really, really impactful.

00:14:57.039 --> 00:14:59.159
And that's why we try to push the data down as low

00:14:59.159 --> 00:15:00.679
in the organization as we can.

00:15:02.119 --> 00:15:04.960
Best places to work is an overall job satisfaction measure.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:07.159
So each of these tiles have a color

00:15:07.159 --> 00:15:10.400
that corresponds to the valence of that score.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:12.479
And they also have a click event

00:15:12.479 --> 00:15:16.520
that shows a drill down in a few different ways.

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:18.039
And this is one of the things we try to do

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:21.559
that's consistent across the different data displays we have.

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:24.520
There's a quick takeaway that you can get just at a glance,

00:15:24.559 --> 00:15:27.520
and then there's more that you can get one level down,

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:29.960
sometimes two, if you really want to.

00:15:31.119 --> 00:15:32.239
So it's great for a briefing

00:15:32.239 --> 00:15:34.119
because you can kind of read the room

00:15:34.119 --> 00:15:36.320
and see where people want to spend their time.

00:15:38.440 --> 00:15:42.239
So in this case, we have scores for the facility,

00:15:42.239 --> 00:15:45.760
its region, the entire healthcare sector of VA,

00:15:45.760 --> 00:15:48.119
and then up to VA overall, just for some context,

00:15:48.119 --> 00:15:50.919
for this year and for last year.

00:15:50.919 --> 00:15:54.559
So everything we show has some comparison data,

00:15:54.559 --> 00:15:56.119
and everything we show also has

00:15:56.119 --> 00:15:57.919
the change score since last year.

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:03.000
Peers shows how the site stacks up

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.559
against other sites in its region.

00:16:05.559 --> 00:16:07.000
So these are other VA facilities

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.440
in the same region as Boston.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:12.840
So people often want to know what rank they are,

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:13.719
how they stack up.

00:16:13.719 --> 00:16:16.400
This gets those questions out of the way early on,

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:20.000
so they can focus on the within-facility data

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:21.960
that's usually more impactful.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.280
Direct reports is one level down in the org chart.

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:31.400
And I should say, too, all these tables and graphs

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:33.080
are sorted by default.

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:38.080
So there's a useful sort based on the scale.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:40.039
So you don't have to kind of orient yourself

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:42.960
to where the high scores are, or the low scores.

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:44.280
They filter automatically.

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:48.880
And that's a small thing, but when you have so much data,

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:51.719
the usability gain you get from that is really important.

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:58.200
The colors correspond to statistical testing of groups.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:01.200
So green is better than a comparison group

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:03.719
or improved since last year.

00:17:03.719 --> 00:17:05.560
Red, of course, is the reverse.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:12.599
And here we can look back to 2018 to get the trajectory.

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:17.640
So each of these has that same ability.

00:17:18.239 --> 00:17:20.479
I'll spare you the details with going through each one,

00:17:20.479 --> 00:17:23.040
but that's the UI piece here.

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:28.920
Each of these also has a breakout

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:32.239
that corresponds to the org chart.

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:34.319
So response rate's chosen by default,

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:37.520
but I'll select best places to work.

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:39.560
So every organization, as I mentioned,

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:42.800
is mapped all the way down to the very small team level,

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.560
five, 10, 15 people.

00:17:45.560 --> 00:17:48.520
So this is a very intuitive display for people,

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:49.680
especially for executives,

00:17:49.680 --> 00:17:51.959
because it matches the schema of the organization

00:17:51.959 --> 00:17:53.119
that they already have.

00:17:54.359 --> 00:17:57.359
The color, of course, corresponds to the value of the score.

00:17:57.359 --> 00:18:01.520
There's a scale up here with VA for reference.

00:18:02.479 --> 00:18:04.119
Again, these numbers, just to reiterate,

00:18:04.119 --> 00:18:05.479
these numbers are fictitious,

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:08.920
but representative of the kind of variance that you see.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
So they stop at two levels down by default,

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.160
just because hospitals are big places.

00:18:16.160 --> 00:18:17.880
But if you want to see everything,

00:18:19.239 --> 00:18:21.680
then you can uncheck that quick map toggle.

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:23.280
And now there's a lot,

00:18:23.280 --> 00:18:25.079
because again, it's a big organization,

00:18:25.079 --> 00:18:27.719
but you can get a quick visual triage

00:18:27.719 --> 00:18:29.520
of the entire organization.

00:18:31.359 --> 00:18:34.319
So you can imagine as a director, as a service chief,

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:38.040
you can really start to see just quickly

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:40.800
where some of the hotspots and bright spots

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:42.280
are within your organization.

00:18:44.839 --> 00:18:47.920
The additional layer of detail here

00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:52.199
is accessed by clicking on the dot.

00:18:52.199 --> 00:18:53.800
So if I wanted to click on,

00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:56.040
I'm just picking a group at random here,

00:18:56.040 --> 00:18:58.359
I can see a drill down into their specific data

00:18:58.359 --> 00:19:03.359
and also a scrambled supervisor email here as mapped locally.

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:06.520
Easy to follow up with people this way.

00:19:08.800 --> 00:19:10.040
I did see a question.

00:19:10.040 --> 00:19:11.040
I'm trying to watch the chat,

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:12.040
but there are lots of questions.

00:19:12.040 --> 00:19:14.839
I saw a question about the URL of the site.

00:19:14.839 --> 00:19:16.239
This is internal to VA,

00:19:16.239 --> 00:19:18.520
so nobody outside of VA could access it.

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:20.800
That's why there's no URL available.

00:19:23.119 --> 00:19:26.439
I can help ask some of the questions too, Ryan.

00:19:26.439 --> 00:19:27.520
Yeah, please.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:28.359
Okay, awesome.

00:19:28.359 --> 00:19:29.319
Yeah, I was just popping in there.

00:19:29.319 --> 00:19:32.280
I didn't want to interrupt the flow though.

00:19:32.280 --> 00:19:36.800
One of the questions that people asked on Slido was,

00:19:37.959 --> 00:19:39.880
I'm new to R and RStudio

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:42.280
and my employer would like their data source

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:45.119
refreshed daily used in their scripts.

00:19:46.439 --> 00:19:48.640
Is Shiny the recommended method?

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:53.560
So we don't do a lot of that, honestly,

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:57.119
because we have sort of large single efforts

00:19:57.119 --> 00:19:59.880
versus kind of continuous incoming data.

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:02.280
I've seen really effective use cases for that.

00:20:03.479 --> 00:20:07.439
I think it depends a lot on the way the data are stored

00:20:07.439 --> 00:20:09.199
and to the extent that you can access it

00:20:09.199 --> 00:20:11.239
through some sort of API or database.

00:20:14.079 --> 00:20:15.479
Thank you.

00:20:15.479 --> 00:20:19.000
Another question that came up earlier was,

00:20:19.880 --> 00:20:23.599
is there any concern from IT regarding the use of R

00:20:23.599 --> 00:20:28.119
and Shiny as the government traditionally uses SaaS?

00:20:28.119 --> 00:20:28.959
Or is this true?

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:33.000
So there is concern.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.479
There is inertia to overcome.

00:20:35.479 --> 00:20:36.880
That's been a process.

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:40.040
You need, at least in my experience,

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:42.839
you need executive sponsorship to be able to say

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:46.680
why the ultimate outcome matters.

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:50.079
Because a lot of IT departments aren't going to care

00:20:50.079 --> 00:20:51.239
about the details of this.

00:20:51.239 --> 00:20:52.719
They care about security.

00:20:52.719 --> 00:20:54.319
They care about maintainability.

00:20:55.479 --> 00:20:57.920
So if you can get somebody at a level

00:20:57.920 --> 00:20:59.719
that has sway with other IT leaders

00:20:59.719 --> 00:21:02.079
to make them care and see the value,

00:21:02.079 --> 00:21:04.079
then you can get more movement that way.

00:21:04.280 --> 00:21:06.880
At least in VA, there's a really detailed process

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:11.880
to go through to get approved to be an app

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:13.880
and to be on, in our case, Azure.

00:21:13.880 --> 00:21:16.359
There's a federal Azure space that we're on.

00:21:16.359 --> 00:21:18.479
So we have to go through all that review,

00:21:19.400 --> 00:21:22.199
which is slow, but you do get there eventually.

00:21:26.479 --> 00:21:28.280
As a follow-up to that,

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:31.479
I love Hugh's comment in the chat.

00:21:31.479 --> 00:21:33.079
Hugh said, this is amazing.

00:21:33.079 --> 00:21:35.880
I work for VHA and this app is so much better

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:38.880
than how we used to get AES results.

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:41.680
You might need to help me on the acronyms here.

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:44.680
But what has been your experience with R and VA?

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:49.079
Thank you for the feedback.

00:21:49.079 --> 00:21:53.079
It's been good, especially for local work.

00:21:53.079 --> 00:21:56.280
So using it on your desktop is not an issue.

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:58.680
It takes an admin to install RStudio,

00:21:58.680 --> 00:22:00.680
but that's typically not a problem.

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:03.479
To get on Azure and get connected

00:22:03.479 --> 00:22:05.680
and then get stood up that way is,

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:07.280
I mentioned a pretty long process.

00:22:07.280 --> 00:22:08.479
It took a couple of years.

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:12.079
There's a lot of contracting and IT

00:22:14.079 --> 00:22:18.079
and related functions that have to be on the same page.

00:22:18.079 --> 00:22:19.680
But I think it's doable.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:21.280
We certainly did it.

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:22.880
It just did take a long time.

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:27.680
Can I ask you a follow-up to that?

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:29.880
Can I ask you a follow-up to that?

00:22:29.880 --> 00:22:34.079
If somebody is listening now and starting that process off,

00:22:34.079 --> 00:22:37.880
what is something that you wish you knew about then

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:39.680
or something that was really helpful

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.079
to you through that process?

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:46.880
Something that is helpful that I wish I had done earlier

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:48.680
is do what I suggest that people do

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:51.280
and have an executive sponsor at a high level

00:22:51.280 --> 00:22:54.079
that comes in to clear some of the obstacles.

00:22:55.079 --> 00:22:57.280
It's like any bureaucracy, I think.

00:22:57.280 --> 00:23:01.680
There are a lot more people who can say no than can say yes.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:04.280
So you need to find that person who can really motivate people

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:06.280
to work on this project on your behalf.

00:23:09.079 --> 00:23:10.680
Thank you.

00:23:10.680 --> 00:23:12.680
I'll save some of the other questions

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:13.880
for a little bit later.

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:15.680
So I'll let you get back to the talk.

00:23:15.680 --> 00:23:16.680
Thank you.

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:18.479
I did see one that's easy to take.

00:23:18.479 --> 00:23:23.079
Limitations on VHA's Azure Space CRAN only or GitHub.

00:23:25.079 --> 00:23:26.680
Haven't run into any limitations yet.

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:30.079
We try to stay with CRAN just for reliability reasons,

00:23:30.079 --> 00:23:32.079
but no issues there.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:35.880
Great. Thank you.

00:23:35.880 --> 00:23:37.680
Sure.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:42.479
So next, we talk about employee engagement and burnout,

00:23:42.479 --> 00:23:45.479
and we do that in the same way

00:23:45.479 --> 00:23:46.880
and with the same kind of interface

00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:48.079
for both of those constructs,

00:23:48.079 --> 00:23:51.680
just, again, for kind of predictability reasons.

00:23:51.680 --> 00:23:54.280
So we talk about engagement in terms of the percent

00:23:54.280 --> 00:23:57.479
of the organization that's engaged versus mixed

00:23:57.479 --> 00:23:59.479
or kind of on the fence, you know,

00:23:59.479 --> 00:24:04.880
maybe engaged sometimes but not always versus disengaged.

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:09.280
So the percents are easy to see here as a bar graph,

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:12.280
and then there's always a change score toggle

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:15.479
that's a plus minus.

00:24:15.479 --> 00:24:18.079
The VA's dots are for reference again.

00:24:18.079 --> 00:24:21.280
So if you're the director of Boston or whatever facility,

00:24:21.280 --> 00:24:25.680
you can easily see where you fall against VA itself.

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:28.880
And then for every bar graph,

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:32.280
the one layer down here is you can click on the bar

00:24:32.280 --> 00:24:35.280
and the little cursor kind of turns into a hand

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:37.880
to kind of cue you into that.

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:41.280
You can click on the bar and see a drill down

00:24:41.280 --> 00:24:45.280
in a few different ways on that specific construct.

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:47.280
So for disengagement here, for example,

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:49.680
we see it by supervisory level

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:54.280
from most disengaged to least.

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:57.479
By service, a lot of variance here.

00:24:57.479 --> 00:24:59.680
Again, fake data, the little banner at the top

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:02.880
gives that away, but you do see, you know, 40,

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:09.079
50, sometimes more points of variance at the service level.

00:25:09.079 --> 00:25:14.079
Work group, again, those small teams of 5, 10, 15 people.

00:25:14.079 --> 00:25:15.680
And you see the most variance here

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:18.280
because people who are in the same occupation

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:20.479
don't all have the same supervisor.

00:25:20.479 --> 00:25:23.880
And so that's why there's usually more variance

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:24.880
at the work group level.

00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:28.880
There's a supervisor effect, basically.

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:30.880
And then info will just have background

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:34.680
on that specific construct.

00:25:34.680 --> 00:25:36.880
So this is nice because we've got, you know,

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:39.880
maybe 15, 20 people doing these briefings,

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:41.880
and some people are more or less familiar

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:43.680
with some of the details of the measures.

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:45.479
So it's a great reference for us,

00:25:45.479 --> 00:25:48.479
but also for our executive audience

00:25:48.479 --> 00:25:51.680
because we leave this app up all year,

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:53.680
and there's a lot of traffic throughout the year.

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:55.479
People come back to it.

00:25:55.479 --> 00:25:57.079
And so you can easily remind yourself

00:25:57.079 --> 00:25:59.479
what the details of that measure are.

00:26:03.079 --> 00:26:05.079
For engagement and for burnout,

00:26:05.079 --> 00:26:08.079
we also have hotspot and bright spot maps.

00:26:08.079 --> 00:26:10.280
So these are like those maps you saw a minute ago,

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:12.880
but now we pull specific groups out

00:26:12.880 --> 00:26:14.880
that have either a concerning score,

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:16.479
in the case of a hotspot,

00:26:16.479 --> 00:26:19.880
or a good score in the case of a bright spot.

00:26:19.880 --> 00:26:23.880
So these are groups where disengagement is at least 50%.

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:26.479
So you get that quick kind of triage,

00:26:26.479 --> 00:26:29.880
and again, capitalizing on the schema of the org chart

00:26:29.880 --> 00:26:34.880
that people are already familiar with.

00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:40.479
Same thing for bright spots, engagement of 75%.

00:26:40.479 --> 00:26:41.880
So in this case, for example,

00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:43.680
it's useful to see the org chart display

00:26:43.680 --> 00:26:46.280
because if you're the chief of social work,

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:47.880
you can see you've got three groups

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:51.680
that meet this threshold.

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:53.479
If it was the reverse and you had three groups

00:26:53.479 --> 00:26:54.880
that met the disengagement threshold,

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.880
there'd be some sort of cluster effect likely.

00:26:57.880 --> 00:26:59.680
So you'd want to know about that.

00:27:04.479 --> 00:27:09.079
So burnout is next, and it's the same kind of display

00:27:09.079 --> 00:27:11.680
for predictability reasons.

00:27:11.680 --> 00:27:13.880
Here we talk about the percent of the organization

00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:17.280
that has zero, one, two, or three

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:21.280
out of three symptoms of burnout at least once a week.

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:22.880
So the more symptoms you have, of course,

00:27:22.880 --> 00:27:25.280
the more burned out you feel.

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:28.079
So the bar graphs show the scores,

00:27:28.079 --> 00:27:31.079
the dots for reference for VA overall,

00:27:31.079 --> 00:27:35.680
the drill downs by clicking on the bar.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:37.280
We have free text themes here as well.

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:39.880
So in the survey that this data comes from,

00:27:40.079 --> 00:27:42.479
people can also leave free text comments,

00:27:42.479 --> 00:27:45.479
and we theme those and report them out verbatim as well.

00:27:45.479 --> 00:27:48.479
We bring in the themes here just as a kind of an idea

00:27:48.479 --> 00:27:50.479
of what's top of mind for people when they're prompted

00:27:50.479 --> 00:27:53.680
to say something about their workplace.

00:27:53.680 --> 00:27:57.479
So as you can probably imagine in healthcare,

00:27:57.479 --> 00:28:01.079
especially now, burnout is top of mind for a lot of folks.

00:28:01.079 --> 00:28:03.079
So you see that quantitatively

00:28:03.079 --> 00:28:07.680
and also qualitatively in the comments.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:12.680
Hotspot and bright spot maps again.

00:28:12.680 --> 00:28:14.280
And then we have two questions,

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:17.280
a lot of bright spots here in this fake set.

00:28:17.280 --> 00:28:19.079
We have two comments about COVID,

00:28:19.079 --> 00:28:22.479
or two questions about COVID rather.

00:28:22.479 --> 00:28:25.680
Extra professional stress because of COVID

00:28:25.680 --> 00:28:28.479
and extra personal stress because of COVID.

00:28:28.479 --> 00:28:30.280
And the scale is from none to extreme,

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:33.280
so you can see the distribution there.

00:28:33.280 --> 00:28:35.479
And then I'll spare you the detail again,

00:28:35.479 --> 00:28:36.479
but you can click on the bar

00:28:36.479 --> 00:28:42.479
and see the same drill downs as you've seen so far.

00:28:42.479 --> 00:28:47.280
Any questions before I jump to the next section?

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:49.680
