00:34:08.879 --> 00:34:13.080
So the next section is a different kind of display,

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:16.679
just a table format here for DE&I data.

00:34:16.679 --> 00:34:19.479
The cool thing here, though, is the comparisons we do,

00:34:19.479 --> 00:34:23.080
not really the display itself.

00:34:23.080 --> 00:34:24.879
So we've got four DE&I questions,

00:34:24.879 --> 00:34:26.479
and those are linked above,

00:34:26.479 --> 00:34:32.479
but we use those and also three overall experience indicators.

00:34:33.479 --> 00:34:36.080
Best places to work, engagement, and burnout.

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:37.879
And for every demographic,

00:34:37.879 --> 00:34:40.479
we test the minority against the majority

00:34:40.479 --> 00:34:42.879
and then shade where the minority

00:34:42.879 --> 00:34:44.879
is lower than the majority.

00:34:44.879 --> 00:34:46.479
So if you see a lot of red, basically,

00:34:46.479 --> 00:34:51.679
it means that in this hypothetical organization,

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:54.280
people who you see have red cells

00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:57.280
are reporting more discrepant experiences

00:34:57.280 --> 00:35:00.479
on the topics you see the red cells for

00:35:01.479 --> 00:35:05.879
than the majority categories for their demographic.

00:35:05.879 --> 00:35:08.280
So for disability status, for example,

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:10.479
people who said they do have a disability,

00:35:10.479 --> 00:35:13.879
21% discrimination versus 11% for people

00:35:13.879 --> 00:35:16.879
who say they don't have a disability.

00:35:16.879 --> 00:35:20.280
And there are two pages because we have so many demographics

00:35:20.280 --> 00:35:22.679
that would make too big of a table to show it at once,

00:35:22.679 --> 00:35:25.280
but as you can imagine,

00:35:25.280 --> 00:35:29.280
this is very interesting for executives to see.

00:35:29.479 --> 00:35:32.280
And there's also change scores, again, available here.

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:36.679
And for those, the comparison is every group to itself last year

00:35:36.679 --> 00:35:38.679
rather than to its majority.

00:35:38.679 --> 00:35:41.080
And if they improve, then they get green

00:35:41.080 --> 00:35:44.679
or whatever you've changed the good color to be.

00:35:44.679 --> 00:35:46.679
If they went down, they get red.

00:35:49.879 --> 00:35:51.679
The next piece of...

00:35:51.679 --> 00:35:54.679
There's three main pieces of DE&I here.

00:35:54.679 --> 00:35:56.479
The next piece is about intersectionality

00:35:56.479 --> 00:35:58.679
because, of course, one demographic

00:35:58.679 --> 00:36:00.879
doesn't describe anybody very well.

00:36:00.879 --> 00:36:03.679
So here you can pick patterns of demographics

00:36:03.679 --> 00:36:07.479
and see how people feel about those same measures,

00:36:07.479 --> 00:36:11.280
but who meet multiple demographic conditions.

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:15.280
Sorted so that it's high to low discrimination.

00:36:15.280 --> 00:36:20.280
And, of course, the coloring is a basic heat map scheme.

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:24.080
And finally, we have hotspots again here

00:36:24.080 --> 00:36:26.080
for those four questions.

00:36:26.080 --> 00:36:27.679
So for each of those questions,

00:36:27.679 --> 00:36:30.080
we can pull, again, those groups out of the org chart

00:36:30.080 --> 00:36:33.879
and see where some concerning scores may be.

00:36:33.879 --> 00:36:35.080
We don't do bright spots here

00:36:35.080 --> 00:36:37.479
because there's no way to know

00:36:37.479 --> 00:36:40.280
whether a group is being very equitable

00:36:40.280 --> 00:36:41.879
and inclusive and so on

00:36:41.879 --> 00:36:44.479
or whether it may just not be a diverse group

00:36:44.479 --> 00:36:46.280
in the first place.

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:48.879
So bright spots are the ones where you can see

00:36:48.879 --> 00:36:51.479
so bright spots wouldn't really work well here,

00:36:51.479 --> 00:36:53.080
but hotspots do.

00:36:59.679 --> 00:37:02.679
Second to last data piece we have here,

00:37:02.679 --> 00:37:05.479
priorities and turnover intent.

00:37:05.479 --> 00:37:07.879
So priorities show what people in the group say

00:37:07.879 --> 00:37:10.879
they most want to work on over the next year.

00:37:10.879 --> 00:37:13.280
So we can see that prioritization,

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:16.679
same click events as before,

00:37:16.679 --> 00:37:18.280
same thing for turnover intent,

00:37:18.280 --> 00:37:20.280
which, as you can imagine, if you're an executive,

00:37:20.280 --> 00:37:22.080
you want to know who's thinking of leaving

00:37:22.080 --> 00:37:26.080
and where you may have some staffing shortages,

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:28.679
and then what's pushing people away.

00:37:28.679 --> 00:37:31.679
So the reasons people who said they want to leave

00:37:31.679 --> 00:37:34.080
gave for wanting to leave in the first place.

00:37:37.280 --> 00:37:41.080
The last data piece here has to do with just culture.

00:37:41.080 --> 00:37:43.479
So if you're not familiar with that term,

00:37:43.479 --> 00:37:45.479
the idea is just that people need to feel,

00:37:45.479 --> 00:37:50.280
especially in safety-critical applications like healthcare,

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:52.479
need to feel like they can speak up

00:37:52.479 --> 00:37:54.479
and say when something's not right,

00:37:54.479 --> 00:37:56.879
but also that there are standards

00:37:56.879 --> 00:37:59.879
and they're transparent and equitable and so on.

00:37:59.879 --> 00:38:03.080
So you want to be up here in this top right area,

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:05.679
and you don't want to be in this off-diagonal.

00:38:05.679 --> 00:38:09.479
So this is a plotly scatterplot.

00:38:09.479 --> 00:38:11.080
The background colors, of course,

00:38:11.080 --> 00:38:15.080
just kind of cue you into where the desirable range of scores

00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:17.479
for these issues are.

00:38:17.479 --> 00:38:20.679
And you can change the questions to get different views.

00:38:20.679 --> 00:38:22.879
You can search and see, for example,

00:38:22.879 --> 00:38:27.879
all nursing groups at once if you wanted to.

00:38:27.879 --> 00:38:30.479
And then you can also toggle between work groups,

00:38:30.479 --> 00:38:34.280
which is the default, and between occupations,

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:37.080
because, again, those are similar but specific.

00:38:39.679 --> 00:38:44.879
And finally, there's a table below that has these same scores.

00:38:45.280 --> 00:38:48.879
But you can also, if you wanted to see the lowest groups all at once,

00:38:48.879 --> 00:38:52.080
you can drag a lasso,

00:38:52.080 --> 00:38:54.879
and the table updates to only show those groups,

00:38:54.879 --> 00:38:58.479
and then you can download this table easily to Excel.

00:39:01.479 --> 00:39:04.080
The tables are using the DT package.

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:09.280
So you get the sortability and the downloading and so forth

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:10.879
kind of by default,

00:39:10.879 --> 00:39:14.879
or at least very easily through that interface.

00:39:19.879 --> 00:39:23.080
Executives usually want to recognize groups that do well,

00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:27.080
so it's easy to get additional resources we make available here

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:30.879
or to see a table that's sorted automatically by default

00:39:30.879 --> 00:39:33.280
just to make it easy to do that.

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:36.280
And then finally, we have just a bunch of extra resources

00:39:36.280 --> 00:39:39.479
that people have gotten used to seeing in VA,

00:39:39.479 --> 00:39:41.479
extra reports, the data stores,

00:39:41.479 --> 00:39:43.280
another app that's on Connect that we made

00:39:43.280 --> 00:39:46.280
that makes it really easy to pull specific data

00:39:46.280 --> 00:39:50.280
in dataset form versus in report form,

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:53.280
other dashboards and tools and videos and so on.

00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:57.679
The bookmark button is great if you're using Connect

00:39:57.679 --> 00:40:01.080
because, or I think Shiny Apps does it also.

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:02.879
This will give you a custom URL

00:40:02.879 --> 00:40:05.879
that remembers all of your input selections.

00:40:05.879 --> 00:40:07.879
So if you're the director of Boston, let's say,

00:40:07.879 --> 00:40:09.479
and you've gotten to this point

00:40:09.479 --> 00:40:11.879
and you've set up the page the way you want,

00:40:11.879 --> 00:40:16.280
you can hit bookmark and then save a URL

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:20.679
that will preload all those same selections for you next time.

00:40:20.679 --> 00:40:23.679
So it's easy to come back and kind of pick up where you left off.

00:40:24.879 --> 00:40:26.479
Hotspot and Brightspot downloads

00:40:26.479 --> 00:40:30.280
just give you Excel files of those groups.

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:34.280
And then this is just a basic bootstrap accordion.

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:37.280
So that's the app.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:40.280
Happy to talk about it more or any piece of it more,

00:40:40.280 --> 00:40:42.280
but that's what I had to show you.

