So if you Google like Microsoft Fluent,

00:43:41.479 --> 00:43:43.479
it'll show you their style guide.

00:43:43.479 --> 00:43:45.479
So it's easy to, well, not easy,

00:43:45.479 --> 00:43:48.479
but it's possible to use CSS to replicate some of that.

00:43:49.479 --> 00:43:53.479
And this matches roughly sort of the Microsoft's corporate-y vibe

00:43:53.479 --> 00:43:56.479
that some of our other enterprise-level applications have.

00:43:56.479 --> 00:44:01.479
So to an executive who isn't checking all these apps all the time,

00:44:01.479 --> 00:44:03.479
it looks familiar and seems credible.

00:44:04.479 --> 00:44:06.479
So that's the point of the aesthetic we have here.

00:44:09.479 --> 00:44:10.479
That's awesome.

00:44:10.479 --> 00:44:14.479
A question that I had was,

00:44:14.479 --> 00:44:18.479
how has the use of the app in these executive briefing sessions

00:44:18.479 --> 00:44:20.479
changed the conversation

00:44:20.479 --> 00:44:25.479
or maybe changed some of the work that the team's doing?

00:44:26.479 --> 00:44:29.479
I think it drives a lot of the work the team does

00:44:29.479 --> 00:44:31.479
and certainly changes it from what it used to be.

00:44:32.479 --> 00:44:36.479
So you could imagine the alternative to this would be,

00:44:36.479 --> 00:44:39.479
you know, a 200-slide PDF or PowerPoint.

00:44:40.479 --> 00:44:41.479
And at that level of detail,

00:44:41.479 --> 00:44:45.479
you're really only taking away the site scores overall.

00:44:45.479 --> 00:44:49.479
You can't focus on where the hot spots and bright spots are, for example,

00:44:49.479 --> 00:44:51.479
because there's just so much.

00:44:52.479 --> 00:44:55.479
So it becomes an issue of support, you know,

00:44:55.479 --> 00:44:58.479
in specific areas for specific topics,

00:44:58.479 --> 00:45:01.479
rather than just sort of letting the data kind of wash over you

00:45:01.479 --> 00:45:04.479
and having a vague impression of how people feel.

00:45:05.479 --> 00:45:06.479
That's the main difference.

00:45:06.479 --> 00:45:09.479
From the bottom-up side, I mentioned a few,

00:45:09.479 --> 00:45:12.479
but the things people are able to do

00:45:12.479 --> 00:45:15.479
as a result of these conversations are really remarkable.

00:45:15.479 --> 00:45:17.479
Backlog reductions and claims,

00:45:17.479 --> 00:45:21.479
better patient handoffs between different care teams and facilities.

00:45:22.479 --> 00:45:24.479
Others are more lighthearted.

00:45:24.479 --> 00:45:26.479
There's just so many things people do.

00:45:29.479 --> 00:45:33.479
I see Jim asked, I realize, a similar question, too.

00:45:34.479 --> 00:45:38.479
And it was, what is the return on investment for the VA?

00:45:39.479 --> 00:45:43.479
It's a lot. It's hard to quantify, as you can imagine.

00:45:43.479 --> 00:45:46.479
You can't put a dollar amount easily on something like,

00:45:47.479 --> 00:45:49.479
you know, smoother patient handoffs

00:45:49.479 --> 00:45:51.479
or better communication on your team.

00:45:52.479 --> 00:45:55.479
Some of the things we quantified had to do with

00:45:57.479 --> 00:46:00.479
claims reduction backlogs of, you know, 5%, 10%,

00:46:00.479 --> 00:46:04.479
which are, you know, at the scale that we have is a lot.

00:46:05.479 --> 00:46:09.479
Savings from duplicative processes across different teams

00:46:09.479 --> 00:46:11.479
that maybe didn't know about it before,

00:46:11.479 --> 00:46:14.479
but they start talking and see that they've both got this ready.

00:46:15.479 --> 00:46:17.479
So, yeah, there's not one number,

00:46:17.479 --> 00:46:20.479
but if there was, I think it would be quite high.

00:46:23.479 --> 00:46:24.479
Great. Thank you.

00:46:25.479 --> 00:46:28.479
I see one other question that just came through on Slido was,

00:46:29.479 --> 00:46:32.479
do you put this shiny app behind any sort of user authentication,

00:46:32.479 --> 00:46:33.479
like Okta?

00:46:35.479 --> 00:46:37.479
No, but that sort of happens for us

00:46:37.479 --> 00:46:40.479
because we're on the federal cloud.

00:46:40.479 --> 00:46:43.479
So to get to it, you have to be on VA's network, basically.

00:46:44.479 --> 00:46:46.479
You have to be in our active directory.

00:46:47.479 --> 00:46:50.479
But beyond that, no, it's open to anybody in VA.

00:46:54.479 --> 00:46:55.479
Great. Thank you.

00:46:57.479 --> 00:46:59.479
One other question I had is,

00:46:59.479 --> 00:47:01.479
if somebody is watching this right now

00:47:01.479 --> 00:47:04.479
and hoping to be able to create an app like this

00:47:04.479 --> 00:47:06.479
and is just getting started,

00:47:07.479 --> 00:47:10.479
what would you recommend for them in learning Shiny?

00:47:12.479 --> 00:47:13.479
That's a good question.

00:47:13.479 --> 00:47:17.479
I would say take it slow, be incremental.

00:47:19.479 --> 00:47:20.479
If you pick some,

00:47:21.479 --> 00:47:24.479
pick your own sophisticated application that you may have seen.

00:47:24.479 --> 00:47:25.479
If you try to do that right away,

00:47:26.479 --> 00:47:28.479
it's probably not going to work and be frustrating.

00:47:29.479 --> 00:47:32.479
So for me, I try to get everything on the screen

00:47:33.479 --> 00:47:34.479
and then do the UI.

00:47:34.479 --> 00:47:36.479
So sort of like how Markdown breaks down the content

00:47:36.479 --> 00:47:37.479
versus the markup.

00:47:39.479 --> 00:47:41.479
I just want to get the data on the screen

00:47:41.479 --> 00:47:44.479
and then I come back and make a formatting pass

00:47:45.479 --> 00:47:46.479
and you revise and iterate.

00:47:47.479 --> 00:47:50.479
So persistence is kind of a boring answer,

00:47:51.479 --> 00:47:52.479
but that's my answer.

00:47:53.479 --> 00:47:55.479
And figuring out how to Google things well

00:47:55.479 --> 00:47:56.479
is a big part of it, too.

00:47:59.479 --> 00:48:02.479
Yeah. What did this app look like in its first stages?

00:48:03.479 --> 00:48:04.479
Not good.

00:48:06.479 --> 00:48:07.479
A lot of the data was there.

00:48:08.479 --> 00:48:09.479
It was a lot slower.

00:48:09.479 --> 00:48:11.479
So I mentioned speed as something that's important.

00:48:13.479 --> 00:48:15.479
Taking another run through the backend

00:48:15.479 --> 00:48:17.479
and focusing on speed was really important.

00:48:19.479 --> 00:48:20.479
If you have a lot of data,

00:48:20.479 --> 00:48:22.479
I haven't found anything faster than data.table.

00:48:24.479 --> 00:48:27.479
I think there may be a tidyverse wrapper package for that,

00:48:28.479 --> 00:48:30.479
but if you need things to happen fast,

00:48:30.479 --> 00:48:32.479
then rdata.table is the way to go.

00:48:36.479 --> 00:48:37.479
Yeah. So how did it look before?

00:48:38.479 --> 00:48:42.479
It was more of a default bootstrap-y type look

00:48:42.479 --> 00:48:45.479
and it didn't fit well on different screen sizes,

00:48:46.479 --> 00:48:47.479
wasn't mobile-friendly,

00:48:47.479 --> 00:48:51.479
so this will reorient itself if you're on a mobile device

00:48:52.479 --> 00:48:54.479
to at least display usably well.

00:48:56.479 --> 00:48:57.479
So it was much more rudimentary before.

00:48:58.479 --> 00:48:59.479
Did you just hit that point

00:48:59.479 --> 00:49:02.479
where you're frustrated with the 200-page PowerPoint,

00:49:02.479 --> 00:49:04.479
or how did you make the switch over?

00:49:06.479 --> 00:49:08.479
It was frustration personally

00:49:08.479 --> 00:49:11.479
and sort of in aggregate across our office

00:49:11.479 --> 00:49:12.479
because we could just tell.

00:49:13.479 --> 00:49:15.479
You sort of know that you're not getting people

00:49:15.479 --> 00:49:18.479
exactly what they need at that level of detail

00:49:18.479 --> 00:49:20.479
with that huge of a presentation,

00:49:21.479 --> 00:49:25.479
but getting to something that could actually scale for us

00:49:26.479 --> 00:49:28.479
is really important because we have 50 people

00:49:28.479 --> 00:49:30.479
versus 420,000.

00:49:31.479 --> 00:49:36.479
So we do reports in Flex Dashboard for every site,

00:49:37.479 --> 00:49:40.479
so figuring out how to do that opened up some doors.

00:49:41.479 --> 00:49:45.479
We do single-page PDFs for every workgroup,

00:49:45.479 --> 00:49:47.479
so 30,000 PDFs.

00:49:49.479 --> 00:49:50.479
Just figuring out how to do it at scale

00:49:50.479 --> 00:49:52.479
was really the barrier for us.

00:49:52.479 --> 00:49:54.479
We knew for a while we could do better,

00:49:54.479 --> 00:49:59.479
but just needed that toolbox to be in place for us.

00:50:02.479 --> 00:50:04.479
I want to make sure I didn't miss anybody's questions,

00:50:04.479 --> 00:50:06.479
so if I did from earlier,

00:50:07.479 --> 00:50:09.479
please feel free to just copy and paste it again

00:50:09.479 --> 00:50:12.479
into YouTube or LinkedIn or Slido.

00:50:12.479 --> 00:50:15.479
I think I've seen everything over on Slido,

00:50:16.479 --> 00:50:17.479
but just want to double-check.

00:50:18.479 --> 00:50:22.479
Ryan, for other government or public sector employees

00:50:22.479 --> 00:50:27.479
who are trying to make the case for open-source technologies

00:50:27.479 --> 00:50:30.479
or being able to use R and Python,

00:50:30.479 --> 00:50:32.479
I know you said finding an executive sponsor

00:50:32.479 --> 00:50:33.479
was really helpful,

00:50:34.479 --> 00:50:36.479
but is there other advice that you have, too?

00:50:38.479 --> 00:50:40.479
Yeah, and this gets to someone else's question

00:50:40.479 --> 00:50:42.479
about ROI as well.

00:50:43.479 --> 00:50:45.479
If you can get contractors,

00:50:45.479 --> 00:50:47.479
if you can get contractors to price you out

00:50:47.479 --> 00:50:49.479
what this looks like for them to do,

00:50:50.479 --> 00:50:52.479
then the ROI becomes quite clear.

00:50:54.479 --> 00:50:59.479
We've had estimates for 100,000-plus for every site,

00:50:59.479 --> 00:51:01.479
so when you have a few hundred sites,

00:51:01.479 --> 00:51:04.479
you're talking dozens of millions of dollars.

00:51:07.479 --> 00:51:09.479
Compared to, I think we have

00:51:09.479 --> 00:51:13.479
a 350-person License Connect contract,

00:51:13.479 --> 00:51:15.479
so the ROI there,

00:51:15.479 --> 00:51:18.479
just in terms of replacement cost, is quite high.

00:51:18.479 --> 00:51:21.479
If you can show that, then that's one option.

00:51:22.479 --> 00:51:24.479
If it's being done, then they're probably paying more for it

00:51:24.479 --> 00:51:28.479
than it would cost to make in-house.

00:51:30.479 --> 00:51:33.479
I would say make sure you go through

00:51:33.479 --> 00:51:36.479
your organization's IT process from the beginning,

00:51:36.479 --> 00:51:37.479
even though it's going to be painful

00:51:37.479 --> 00:51:40.479
and you're going to want to lean on that executive

00:51:40.479 --> 00:51:42.479
to get you around certain barriers.

00:51:42.479 --> 00:51:44.479
Make sure you're still checking all the boxes,

00:51:44.479 --> 00:51:47.479
because when it comes time to maintain your system

00:51:47.479 --> 00:51:50.479
or if the maintenance contractor changes,

00:51:50.479 --> 00:51:52.479
there are all sorts of things that can happen,

00:51:52.479 --> 00:51:54.479
and then you fall through the cracks.

00:51:54.479 --> 00:51:57.479
Or maybe your sponsor moves on

00:51:57.479 --> 00:51:59.479
and then you have to get funding again.

00:51:59.479 --> 00:52:03.479
So do it slowly but the right way, I think,

00:52:03.479 --> 00:52:06.479
versus trying to reach for that

00:52:06.479 --> 00:52:09.479
kind of skip to the front of the line method,

00:52:09.479 --> 00:52:11.479
even though it's attractive.

00:52:13.479 --> 00:52:15.479
Thank you. I see one question I...

00:52:15.479 --> 00:52:17.479
Oh, it just disappeared.

00:52:17.479 --> 00:52:20.479
One question I think I missed earlier was

00:52:20.479 --> 00:52:26.479
someone asked, have you looked at Arrow or Parquet

00:52:26.479 --> 00:52:29.479
instead of Data.table?

00:52:29.479 --> 00:52:31.479
I know the term Arrow.

00:52:31.479 --> 00:52:34.479
I haven't done any more looking into it than that

00:52:34.479 --> 00:52:36.479
because Data.table's been fast enough for us.

00:52:36.479 --> 00:52:40.479
But I know there are newer alternatives, yeah.

00:52:40.479 --> 00:52:42.479
I think they're in some of the Data.table benchmarks

00:52:42.479 --> 00:52:44.479
that I saw last.

00:52:45.479 --> 00:52:47.479
Cool.

00:52:47.479 --> 00:52:49.479
One other follow-up question on that example you said

00:52:49.479 --> 00:52:54.479
of going through the IT process very early.

00:52:54.479 --> 00:53:00.479
How did you build relationships with the IT team?

00:53:00.479 --> 00:53:04.479
And is it centrally managed by IT now?

00:53:04.479 --> 00:53:05.479
Sort of.

00:53:05.479 --> 00:53:09.479
So there's a more central decision-making body

00:53:10.479 --> 00:53:13.479
and sort of a more distributed implementation body

00:53:13.479 --> 00:53:17.479
is sort of the rough lay of the land.

00:53:17.479 --> 00:53:21.479
You start to at least get name recognition with folks

00:53:21.479 --> 00:53:26.479
and then depending on where your organization is positioned,

00:53:26.479 --> 00:53:29.479
you may have additional overlap with some IT functions.

00:53:29.479 --> 00:53:34.479
Like we have a few other things we do that put us on IT's radar.

00:53:34.479 --> 00:53:36.479
So they knew a little bit about us

00:53:36.479 --> 00:53:38.479
and it wasn't like we're a complete stranger

00:53:38.479 --> 00:53:40.479
coming into them.

00:53:40.479 --> 00:53:44.479
And to be fair to them also, at least for us,

00:53:44.479 --> 00:53:46.479
I know other agencies look different,

00:53:46.479 --> 00:53:50.479
but the scale of VA IT, like us coming with this,

00:53:50.479 --> 00:53:56.479
is sort of like asking a shipyard to build a kayak.

00:53:56.479 --> 00:53:58.479
It's sort of in the ballpark of the thing they do,

00:53:58.479 --> 00:54:01.479
but it's just such a different scale

00:54:01.479 --> 00:54:04.479
and it's not related directly to patient care.

00:54:04.479 --> 00:54:06.479
It's not a benefits processing system.

00:54:06.479 --> 00:54:09.479
So it's a little bit outside their immediate concern.

00:54:09.479 --> 00:54:12.479
So being understanding of their reality too,

00:54:12.479 --> 00:54:13.479
I think is important.

00:54:13.479 --> 00:54:17.479
Showing some empathy and just being persistent

00:54:17.479 --> 00:54:20.479
really is the best advice I can give.

00:54:20.479 --> 00:54:22.479
Great, thank you.

